\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_002\": 0.90, \"rxn_003\": 0.80, \"rxn_004\": 0.90, \"rxn_009\": 0.78},\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.82,\n      \"feedback\": \"Nogal et al. 2024 demonstrated 33% yield for NADH-mediated reductive amination of \u03b1-KG. However, NADH (mol_016) appears with no synthesis pathway in the network \u2014 it is a complex nucleotide cofactor whose prebiotic availability is highly uncertain. The Hydrothermal \u2192 Biochemical transition is appropriate but the NADH gap weakens confidence. The Biochemical environment label is justified since this bridges toward enzymatic-type chemistry.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Add a synthesis or sourcing pathway for NADH, or replace with a simpler hydride donor (e.g., dihydropyridines or cyanoborohydride as in Mayer & Moran 2022).\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_002\": 0.90, \"rxn_003\": 0.80, \"rxn_004\": 0.90, \"rxn_010\": 0.82},\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n      \"feedback\": \"UV-pyrite photocatalytic reductive amination is a recent and compelling finding (Nature Communications 2024). The Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface environmental progression is well-justified: hydrothermal products from deep vents transported to UV-irradiated shallow pools/mineral surfaces. The pyrite photocatalysis also introduces interesting chirality implications (14.5\u201342.4% D-excess). Solid pathway.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify UV wavelength range and pyrite surface conditions; note the D-amino acid excess from this route.\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_011\": 0.75, \"rxn_012\": 0.85},\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.55,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.60,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.70,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.63,\n      \"feedback\": \"Critical flaw: acrolein (mol_013) has no production reaction in the network \u2014 it appears as an intermediate but is effectively an unconnected starting material. Van Trump and Miller 1972 identified acrolein as the key Strecker precursor, but its prebiotic source is unclear. The Strecker mechanism itself is sound (Parker et al. 2011 confirmed it). HCN (mol_005) also lacks a production reaction but is more easily justified as a volcanic/atmospheric feedstock. Only Surface environment \u2014 no environmental interconnection.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Add a reaction producing acrolein (e.g., from propargyl alcohol or aldol condensation of formaldehyde + acetaldehyde); add HCN source reaction (e.g., atmospheric CH\u2084/N\u2082 photochemistry or volcanic outgassing); improve environmental diversity.\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_013\": 0.60},\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.58,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.50,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.45,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.55,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.52,\n      \"feedback\": \"Single-step HCN oligomerization to glutamic acid is an oversimplification. Ferris et al. 1978 showed glutamate as a trace product among many from HCN oligomer hydrolysis, but the mechanism involves multiple intermediates (diaminomaleonitrile, oligomers, etc.) not represented. Glutamate yield is very low. Single Surface environment with no mineral agent specified. HCN source missing. This pathway is too reductive to be convincing as presented.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Expand into multi-step mechanism including HCN tetramerization, oligomerization, and staged hydrolysis; specify HCN concentration requirements (~0.01 M minimum); add eutectic freezing or evaporative concentration step; note very low glutamate selectivity.\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_014\": 0.75, \"rxn_015\": 0.72, \"rxn_012\": 0.85},\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.75,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.65,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.75,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n      \"feedback\": \"Cyanosulfidic route is conceptually sound, drawing on Patel et al. 2015 and Sutherland's work. However, rxn_014 (HCN + H\u2082S \u2192 acrylonitrile) requires Cu-photoredox cycling and UV irradiation \u2014 conditions should be specified. rxn_015 (acrylonitrile + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 glutamate aminonitrile) involves conjugate addition that is plausible but less directly demonstrated for this specific product. All Surface \u2014 limited environmental diversity. HCN source missing from network.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify Cu\u00b2\u207a/Cu\u207a photoredox cycling and UV conditions for rxn_014; provide experimental reference for rxn_015 specificity; add HCN production reaction.\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_002\": 0.90, \"rxn_003\": 0.80, \"rxn_005\": 0.85, \"rxn_006\": 0.85},\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.72,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.82,\n      \"feedback\": \"Combines Stubbs et al. 2020 metal-free aldol chemistry with FeS reductive amination. The environmental flow is somewhat