recursor. The network's major strengths: (1) strong literature grounding \u2014 Muchowska et al. 2019, Stubbs et al. 2020, Kaur et al. 2024, Nogal et al. 2024, and Mayer & Moran 2022 are all appropriately invoked; (2) four well-connected hub molecules with \u03b1-KG at degree \u2265 7; (3) 10 distinct pathways providing genuine redundancy; (4) the glyoxylate regeneration cycle in transamination pathways; (5) the reactivity paradox is implicitly addressed by providing multiple amination routes. Notable weaknesses: (1) HCN (mol_005) is labeled as hub_intermediate but has no production reaction \u2014 it should either be reclassified as starting material or given a synthesis route (e.g., atmospheric/volcanic); (2) acrolein (mol_013) has no source, making P6 incomplete; (3) NADH (mol_016) has no synthesis route, weakening P4; (4) the HCN oligomerization pathway (P7) is oversimplified; (5) several intermediates (oxaloacetate mol_018, acetate mol_019) are defined but unused in any reaction, creating orphan nodes; (6) the network correctly represents individual step successes but should acknowledge Kaur et al. 2024's critical negative result that one-pot integration fails for glutamate. Despite these issues, the core protometabolic pathways (P1-P5, P9-P10) are chemically sound, well-supported, and achieve the target convincingly. The network topology is strong with genuine convergent synthesis.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.88,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.90\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.9, "rxn_003": 0.8, "rxn_004": 0.9, "rxn_006": 0.85}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.86, "pathway_coherence": 0.9, "environmental_progression": 0.8, "target_achievement": 0.88, "overall_confidence": 0.86, "feedback": "Strong protometabolic pathway supported by Muchowska et al. 2019 and Hafenbradl et al. 1995. Fe\u2070 \u2192 pyruvate/glyoxylate is well-demonstrated (Varma et al. 2018). Fe\u00b2\u207a-pro