     },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.83,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.84,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"Classic W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user route. Hafenbradl et al. 1995 demonstrated FeS/H\u2082S-driven reductive amination at 100\u00b0C. All steps remain in hydrothermal environment which is environmentally coherent. The FeS/H\u2082S system is well-characterized for alkaline hydrothermal vents. Yield data for \u03b1-KG specifically is limited compared to simpler keto acids.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Provide yield estimates or selectivity data for FeS/H\u2082S reductive amination of \u03b1-KG specifically versus simpler keto acids\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.83,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_022\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_021\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.85\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.84,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n      \"feedback\": \"Clever route using hydroxylamine, directly supported by Muchowska et al. 2019 who used Fe\u2070 + hydroxylamine to generate amino acids including glutamate. Lightning NO\u2093 production (rxn_022) is geochemically well-established. FeS reduction of NO to NH\u2082OH (rxn_021) supported by Summers and Chang 1993 though they report NH\u2083 as product more than NH\u2082OH \u2014 the hydroxylamine intermediate may need better support. rxn_021 labeled Surface but FeS reduction might be more appropriate as Hydrothermal.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_021\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify whether FeS reduction of NO produces NH\u2082OH versus NH\u2083 preferentially\", \"Consider relabeling rxn_021 environment\", \"Specify mineral agent for rxn_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.87,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.86,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"Classic and extremely well-supported pathway. Van Trump and Miller 1972 identified acrolein as the key Strecker precursor for glutamate. Parker et al. 2011 confirmed the mechanism. Miller 1955, Johnson et al. 2008 detected glutamate in spark discharge products. The Strecker pathway through aminonitrile intermediate is one of the most established prebiotic synthesis routes. rxn_013 producing multiple products from spark discharge is realistic. All steps in Surface environment is appropriate for atmospheric/photochemical chemistry followed by aqueous Strecker reactions. Minor concern: acrolein yield from spark discharge is low.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Note that glutamate is a minor product via this route \u2014 yield data from Miller experiments shows trace quantities\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.60\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.68,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.70,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.65,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.70,\n      \"feedback\": \"Weakest pathway. While Ferris et al. 1978 showed HCN oligomer hydrolysis releases amino acids including glutamate, the selectivity for glutamate specifically is very poor. HCN oligomers (DAMN and higher) produce a complex mixture; glutamate would be a very minor component. The mechanism of how C\u2085 amino acid structure emerges from HCN oligomers is not well-characterized. HCN concentration problem (requires >0.01 M) noted in literature. rxn_018 is the most problematic \u2014 claiming glutamic acid as a specific product of oligomer hydrolysis is an oversimplification.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Acknowledge very low selectivity and yield for glutamate from this route\", \"Consider whether this pathway should produce a mixture of amino acids rather than targeting glutamate specifically\", \"Address HCN concentration requirements (eutectic freezing)\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_019\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_020\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n      \"feedback\": \"Cyanosulfidic pathway drawing on Patel et al. 2015 and Sutherland group chemistry. rxn_019 (HCN + H\u2082S \u2192 acrylonitrile) is simplified \u2014 the actual cyanosulfidic network involves Cu-photoredox cycling and more complex intermediates. Direct reaction of HCN with H\u2082S more typically yields thiocyanate or thioformamide, not acrylonitrile directly. The conjugate addition of HCN to acrylonitrile (rxn_020) to form glutamic acid aminonitrile is chemically reasonable (Michael addition). Overall a plausible but somewhat oversimplified representation of the Sutherland network.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Include Cu\u00b2\u207a photoredox catalyst and UV light in rxn_019\", \"Show the actual cyanosulfidic mechanism more accurately \u2014 acrylonitrile formation requires additional steps\", \"Consider adding Cu\u00b2\u207a as a molecule node\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is an excellent and comprehensive synthesis network for prebiotic glutamic acid. The network demonstrates outstanding topology with \u03b1-KG as a central hub (degree 8) and HCN as a secondary hub (degree 6), creating genuine convergence. The strategy of providing six distinct amination chemistries to address the Mayer & Moran reactivity paradox is both scientifically sound and strategically clever. The network aligns remarkably well with the literature: Muchowska et al. 2019, Stubbs et al. 2020, Kaur et al. 2024, Nogal et al. 2024, Van Trump & Miller 1972, Hafenbradl et al. 1995, and Patel et al. 2015 are all faithfully represented. The glyoxylate regeneration cycle in P1 (consumed in rxn_005, regenerated in rxn_007) adds catalytic elegance. Key strengths: (1) multiple independent routes to target with different feedstocks, (2) proper acknowledgment of Kaur et al. 2024 one-pot failure, (3) production reactions for all intermediates including HCN, acrolein, glycine, and hydroxylamine. Weaknesses: (1) rxn_003 (direct CO\u2082 \u2192 glyoxylate) needs stronger experimental support, (2) NADH is used but not produced in the network, (3) rxn_019 oversimplifies cyanosulfidic chemistry, (4) rxn_018 (HCN oligomers \u2192 glutamate) has very low selectivity. The network would benefit from addressing pyroglutamate cyclization as a stability concern and from including Bennu/Ryugu racemic results that constrain extraterrestrial chirality hypotheses. Overall, this is one of the most thorough and literature-aligned prebiotic synthesis networks possible for glutamic acid.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.93,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.91\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.88, "rxn_002": 0.83, "rxn_003": 0.75, "rxn_004": 0.8, "rxn_005": 