t a strong oxidant\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_005\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.78,\n                \"rxn_019\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n            \"feedback\": \"The oxaloacetate branch provides an alternative route to \u03b1-KG via TCA-like chemistry. Pyruvate carboxylation to OAA (rxn_010) requires either biotin-like cofactor or CO\u2082 under high pressure; this is plausible in Hydrothermal settings but the specific mineral catalyst should be specified. The OAA\u2192\u03b1-KG step (rxn_011) via glyoxylate is part of the Muchowska network. This adds network redundancy which is valuable.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify the mineral catalyst for pyruvate carboxylation; consider thiamine-like cofactors or metal-carbonate chemistry\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_002\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_024\": 0.85\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n            \"feedback\": \"An elegant short pathway combining Stubbs et al. 2020 metal-free \u03b1-KG synthesis with the 2024 pyrite UV photocatalysis finding. Both steps have direct experimental support. The pathway operates entirely at the Surface, which is coherent for UV